<span id="freeTextContainer16251411796813019277">How are these books not even on my list, much less missing from my favourites list?<br/><br/>The Song of Albion trilogy is still right up there with the best fantasy I&apos;ve ever read. It captured my imagination like nothing else I had read before it, and in the same way that Lord of the Rings and Harry Potter managed to (when I read them both years after Lawhead&apos;s trilogy).<br/><br/>These are three books I generally try to read every year or so. Amazing. Easily Lawhead&apos;s best work, although &apos;Patrick&apos; and &apos;Byzantium&apos; </span>
  <span id="freeText16251411796813019277" style="display:none">How are these books not even on my list, much less missing from my favourites list?<br /><br />The Song of Albion trilogy is still right up there with the best fantasy I've ever read. It captured my imagination like nothing else I had read before it, and in the same way that Lord of the Rings and Harry Potter managed to (when I read them both years after Lawhead's trilogy).<br /><br />These are three books I generally try to read every year or so. Amazing. Easily Lawhead's best work, although 'Patrick' and 'Byzantium' are right up there, along with the Pendragon books.</span>
